  "info": {
    "title": "GraphQL",
    "description": "<div id=\"overview_graphql\">...\n  <h2>GraphQL</h2>\n  <p>The GraphQL API provides queries and mutations to the same resources stored on the Kibo platform as those of the REST API.   \n  A full listing of the queries and mutations can be retrieved from the GraphQL schema which can be obtained via <a href='https://graphql.org/learn/introspection/' >introspection</a> or via the Documentation Explorer in the GraphQL playground located in the root of your site /graphql or thru the Graphql Voyager located [yoursite]/graphql/voyager. You can also find more information and examples for Kibo's usage of GraphQL in the <a href=\"https://docs.kibocommerce.com/help/graphql\">extended user guide</a> on the knowledge base.\n  </p>\n  <h3>GraphQL Playground </h3>\n  <p>\n  To access the GraphQL Storefront API Playground and documentation view your sites web front end ( so that a cookie can be set ) and then navigate to /graphql.  </>\n  <p>Then click the settings gear in the upper right corner and set  <code> \"request.credentials\": \"include\"</code>\n  </p>\n  <p><img src='graphql_settings.jpg' ></p>\n  <p>From there you can make any storefront calls allowed by a shopper.\n  </p>\n  <p><img src='graphql_1.jpg'></p>\n  <p>To make admistrative calls.  Use a jwt token gotten from the application development <a href='/?spec=add_dev#post-/platform/applications/authtickets/oauth'>oauth authenticate method.</a>\n</div>\n",
    "version": "1.0.1"
  },
